with their mouth.

307
00:18:52,131 --> 00:18:55,431
You want the kid to learn to
burp his way through his conversation?

308
00:18:55,501 --> 00:19:00,769
Mm. I don't think it would be possible
to sustain enough air output to...

309
00:19:00,840 --> 00:19:03,309
- It was a joke, Murphy.
- Oh.

310
00:19:04,310 --> 00:19:06,905
Snoring is a better model anyway.

311
00:19:06,979 --> 00:19:10,040
Soft palate tissue vibrates,
making the sound when people snore,

312
00:19:10,149 --> 00:19:12,229
but it's not stiff enough
to replace the vocal cords,

313
00:19:12,451 --> 00:19:15,216
but we could use
his own costal cartilage

314
00:19:15,321 --> 00:19:16,949
to act as vocal cords.

315
00:19:17,857 --> 00:19:20,486
The larynx is a complicated piece
of anatomy.

316
00:19:20,559 --> 00:19:22,187
Basically, a tiny musical instrument.

317
00:19:22,294 --> 00:19:25,662
We can remove two of his ribs
to create

318
00:19:25,731 --> 00:19:27,666
the anterior
and posterior larynx frame,

319
00:19:27,733 --> 00:19:30,328
and then stretch
the cartilage across it.

320
00:19:30,436 --> 00:19:33,235
And then cut open a trachea we worked
so hard to close?

321
00:19:33,339 --> 00:19:35,831
We could destroy
everything we just fixed.

322
00:19:36,208 --> 00:19:37,208
Yes.

323
00:19:37,743 --> 00:19:39,541
I think it's worth the risk.

324
00:19:40,946 --> 00:19:43,074
Because you're thinking
the kid's like you.

325
00:19:43,182 --> 00:19:45,674
That he needs to speak out loud
to be understood.

326
00:19:48,954 --> 00:19:50,047
She's right.

327
00:19:52,658 --> 00:19:55,059
The larynx is like
a musical instrument...

328
00:19:55,361 --> 00:19:58,195
but if Bo Diddley can make a guitar
out of a cigar box,

329
00:19:58,264 --> 00:20:01,325
I'm pretty sure I can make a larynx
from bone and cartilage.

330
00:20:04,770 --> 00:20:05,897
Oh.

331
00:20:07,039 --> 00:20:08,337
Absolutely not.

332
00:20:08,407 --> 00:20:11,241
He's finally healthy.
There's no need to take any more risks.

333
00:20:11,343 --> 00:20:13,175
You're right,
there are definitely risks,

334
00:20:13,245 --> 00:20:15,976
but I wouldn't present the option
if we couldn't manage them.

335
00:20:16,048 --> 00:20:18,074
Couldn't we wait
until he's a few years older?

336
00:20:18,184 --> 00:20:20,244
I assume the stronger he is,
the safer it is.

337
00:20:20,352 --> 00:20:23,880
Most verbal language development
happens within the first eight years.

338
00:20:24,490 --> 00:20:25,788
Cory's already 10.

339
00:20:26,058 --> 00:20:29,893
If we wait any longer, he may not be able
to learn to speak even with a larynx.

340
00:20:29,995 --> 00:20:31,896
He can communicate without speaking.

341
00:20:33,766 --> 00:20:36,565
- You're making a big mistake.
- Murphy...

342
00:20:36,635 --> 00:20:39,537
He'll always be... limited.

343
00:20:40,005 --> 00:20:43,772
It'll be difficult to make friends,
to interact with strangers.

344
00:20:43,876 --> 00:20:45,310
Murphy, that's enough.

345
00:20:46,045 --> 00:20:48,810
They're aware of their options,
and they've made their decision.

346
00:21:08,300 --> 00:21:10,030
The suture repair looks fine,

347
00:21:10,102 --> 00:21:12,230
which makes me think
the nerve got compressed

348
00:21:12,304 --> 00:21:14,170
between the bone and the dog's teeth.

349
00:21:14,273 --> 00:21:16,333
It's too wide to repair with a graft.

350
00:21:16,942 --> 00:21:20,071
What if we built a nerve conduit
out of silicone and polyglycolide?

351
00:21:20,146 --> 00:21:22,809
We could guide the severed nerve ends
to grow toward each other.

352
00:21:22,915 --> 00:21:24,715
Create a pathway for them
to connect and heal.

353
00:21:24,784 --> 00:21:27,151
I'm not sure the nerves can grow
across that distance.

354
00:21:27,253 --> 00:21:28,619
It's definitely worth a try.

355
00:21:28,687 --> 00:21:30,918
We can't just
experiment on her like a lab rat.

356
00:21:30,990 --> 00:21:32,982
We can't just sit back
and do nothing.

357
00:21:33,092 --> 00:21:35,857
I'm not saying do nothing,
we just can't experiment on her blindly.

358
00:21:35,961 --> 00:21:38,123
Maybe we could use donor tissue
to bridge the gap.

359
00:21:38,197 --> 00:21:40,428
